body: Here's some information that is definately relevant:  The 2013 Police Executive Research Forum (PERF) review of U.S. Customs and Border Protection use-of-force cases found a recurring and deeply troubling pattern in vehicle-related shootings. In multiple cases, officers intentionally placed themselves in the path of a moving or fleeing vehicle, then claimed an imminent threat to life when the vehicle continued moving‚Äîthereby creating a justification for deadly force that would not have existed had they simply moved out of the way.  PERF explicitly states that many drivers were non-violent suspects attempting to flee, not using the vehicle as a weapon. The report notes that officers frequently ignored safer tactical alternatives (stepping aside, maintaining distance, using cover) and instead manufactured a deadly-force scenario by inserting themselves into the vehicle‚Äôs exit path. PERF also emphasized that shooting at vehicles is tactically unsound: bullets rarely stop a car, disabling a driver can turn the vehicle into an unguided hazard, and bystanders‚Äîincluding passengers‚Äîare placed at extreme risk.  As a result, PERF recommended a categorical policy change: officers must not shoot at moving vehicles unless the occupants are using deadly force by means other than the vehicle itself, and officers must be trained to avoid positioning themselves in front of vehicles rather than exploiting that position to justify lethal force.   Application to the killing of Renee Good In the context of Renee Good, the conduct visible in the videos aligns disturbingly well with the exact failure mode identified by PERF more than a decade ago. Multiple camera angles show the vehicle steering away, not toward the officer; yet Jonathan Ross steps into the vehicle‚Äôs path, fires through the windshield, and fires again as the car passes‚Äîa textbook example of an officer creating the very danger he then claims to be responding to. Given Ross‚Äôs decade of experience, the PERF findings, and the long-standing law-enforcement consensus that officers must not put themselves in front of vehicles, it is not speculative to conclude that this tactic‚Äîand its lethal ‚Äújustification‚Äù‚Äîwas understood in advance. The threat was not unavoidable; it was manufactured. Under the standards PERF articulated, this was not self-defense but a deliberate escalation into deadly force that policy exists specifically to prevent.

body: so i've rewatched it many times, and paused where needed.  the officer is some feet away from the passenger side of the vehicle (i.e. nowhere near being in front of the car). the wife is saying "come at me" and she and agent are arguing.  then Renee backs up her vehicle, looking behind (over her left shoulder) to back up. meanwhile, the officer is *very quickly* crossing in front of the vehicle, over to the driver's side, while Renee is reversing and not looking ahead.  then, by the time Renee is looking forward again, she is wanting to flee and escape, the officer had *unexpectedly* passed to the opposite side of her vehicle and was now in the way of it. Renee would have already been accelerating forward by the time she had realized he was in the path. meanwhile she was turning her wheel to the right when he was to the left. so obviously she did not hit him on purpose.  this is why they teach children to not walk in front of moving vehicles.  at worst, she was a reckless driver (ICE does not have the legal right to detain citizens so she was not wrong to attempt to flee the scene).  i've been in a situation before where i was a pedestrian at an intersection and "walk" sign is on, but people turning left on a solid green don't realize they need to give me the right-of-way. so i was once hit by someone's mirror because they are a terrible driver. by the logic of some comments here, i should have been allowed to pull out a gun and open fire on the driver for this. however you spin it, this was his mistake and his fault, and a terrible and tragic overreaction.

body: As a veteran former cop, the first thing I told people about this situation was, you have the wrong tool for the wrong job. You outlined it perfectly talking about ICE probably not receiving the same level of crow control tactics training as the local agencies.  Federal agencies are designed to work in specific areas and focus on specific issues. Their officers are provided basic law enforcement training but the majority of their training specializes in their specific field. So now we have unsupported federal agents working in a situation where they are dealing with the general public. That‚Äôs not what they‚Äôre used to. They don‚Äôt handle these situations like local officers do. It‚Äôs a shame to see how polarized this country is and how we refuse to support each other.

Not because the world ends suddenly, but because humanity has already been undoing itself, quietly.  Not by fire or collapse, but by policies without conscience, by power without mercy, by the long refusal to choose goodness when it was still within reach.  Because a system that hunts the vulnerable cannot call itself just.  Papers do not decide humanity. Workers are not criminals for feeding families, for crossing lines due to desperation.  If cruelty must disguise itself as order, then it is not order at all.  And history will remember who enforced the harm long after the excuses are gone -L.D.

Also, there are other people shown in the video with cell phone recording, I would like to see their videos as well.  From what I've seen, this video footage by Max Shapiro appears the most clean to my eyes, even though the views are distant and sometimes blocked by people in the foreground. body: [3:58] No. No. No.  All too often, this bullsh%t about _"did he _*_FEEL_*_ his life was in danger"_ is a crock of bullsh%t **EXCUSE** .  OF COURSE anybody is going to SAY _"I felt my life was in danger.,_ and too often police have used it as an excuse to justify a shooting that THEY instigated.   And it is EXACTLY for that reason that an OBJECTIVE standard should be applied that is outside of that individual's state of mind.    The legal standard is *not* _"did that person believe their life was in danger?"_  The legal standard is _"would a REASONABLE MIND have felt that their life was in danger."_  And in THIS CASE, a person who has *already taken the ONE step necessary to get out of the potential path of the vehicle, and who had to LEAN BACK INTO THE PATH of the vehicle just to fire his gun into the vehicle* is ***NOT*** a person who is reasonably in fear for his life or safety.  PERIOD.

body: 1) The victim was seen moments beforehand, only holding a mobile phone (right hand, filming) while standing still on the road when he was approached by 1 BPC/ICE agent in view. No visible gun. Not in the shop to start with as early reports claimed. Agent pushed him back towards the sidewalk. 2) another video showed agents pushing women to the kurb, 1 is pushed violently to the ground then is shielded by the victim. They are both pepper sprayed The victim was sprayed a 2nd time in the face, hunched over then dragged into a melee. His hands were up around his head as he was squatting on the ground. His vision & breathing would be affected, probably disoriented & reacting to being hit multiple times including the metal spray can into his head. By this time he could not effectively use a gun.  3) The gun shown is possibly an ICE issued weapon, no blood visible. The victim not sern holding nor carrying the gun while being filmed in published videos. 4) Another video showed from when more agents converge & try to detain him. Not sure if during the scuffle, an agent has found/dropped/fumbled a gun & there may have been an accidental discharge or initial reaction to finding the gun. From previous video appears hands near ground & away from waist (his & theirs). After 1 shot, it looks like panic, confusion & chaos with atleast 10 more shots fired by agent(s) into a non-moving body (atleast not moving after 3 shots, maybe earlier).  5) Aged 37 & believed to be an USA citizen, no serious criminal convictions, only vehicle/driving tickets. Not the 51yo violent illegal alien as first reported which they may have been looking for in the area.  Requires unbiased independent coronial & legal process to investigate. Public needs all the facts, not lies, distortions & misleading statements.

body: The man brutally murdered by ICE in Minneapolis today FOR NO REASON has been identified as 37-year-old Minneapolis resident and American CITIZEN Alex Jeffrey Pretti.  Alex was a registered nurse with NO CRIMINAL RECORD and only a few parking tickets to his name. He was an athlete and avid outdoorsman. He was a brother and a son. He worked for the VA, where he cared for veterans' health. He was an ICE observer who was legally filming the ICE agents‚Äô actions when he was stopped, detained, DISARMED, and THEN shot several times by ICE agents. Alex had a legal permit to carry a firearm and multiple videos of the killing clearly show that he did not draw his weapon or brandish it at ICE agents. Apparently, the Second Amendment only applies to Republicans. He was ONLY filming when they approached him, and was ONLY holding his camera. ICE agents had taken his weapon from its holster BEFORE they shot him. He was being pinned down and brutally beaten by a mob of ICE agents when they shot him FOR NO REASON. It was MURDER. It's worth highlighting the fact that Pretti is a legal citizen and has an address listed in South Minneapolis. The Trump administration has flooded our streets with undertrained, overweight, bloodthirsty, masked enforcers under the pretext of rounding up violent undocumented migrants. In practice, they're targeting and executing innocent Americans. It's absolutely paramount that we spread the truth about Pretti far and wide because Homeland Security is already rushing to falsely smear him as an attempted mass shooter. body: Gaslighting works   when it regulates fear   faster   than truth can land.    brain asks only one question:    ‚ÄúWhat story lets me feel safe right now?‚Äù    Not: ‚ÄúWhat is true?‚Äù    Under threat,   most humans side with whoever looks strongest.    Because strength feels like protection.    So     even if the act is horrifying, people unconsciously think:   ‚ÄúI‚Äôd rather be aligned with power   than exposed to chaos.‚Äù    That alignment dulls moral clarity.    Language anesthetizes violence  Words like:    ‚Äúself-defense‚Äù  ‚Äúprotocol‚Äù  ‚Äúincident‚Äù  ‚Äúofficer-involved‚Äù  do not describe reality.    They numb it.    The brain hears abstraction   instead of blood.    Abstraction reduces empathy.     Reduced empathy allows denial.    Eventually people say: ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know what really happened.‚Äù    Admitting the truth   would require people to face:    complicity  powerlessness  horror  That is unbearable for many.    So they choose the story that lets them stay psychologically intact.    This is not courage.   This is self-preservation through denial.    The more emotional the truth is delivered,   the more people cling to the lie   that calms them.    That is the trap.    Repetition does not persuade.   It normalizes.    Once a phrase is heard enough times,   the brain treats it as familiar.    Familiar feels safe.   Safe feels true.    Gaslighting works   not because the lie is good,  but because the truth is too destabilizing   for most people to hold.    you would rather be horrified   than anesthetized  That puts you in the minority.    This is not new.   This is how every violent system survives.

body: Unfortunately, there are approximately 5 videos that have come out about this incident, but the ones most used are the ones that that show the least. The ones filmed from the opposite side of the street show more, a lot more.     (1) Ross used his right hand when he began filming with his cell phone. (2) However, when he positioned himself in front on the car to block it from escaping, he shifted the phone to his left hand with the clear intention of freeing his right hand to shoot Good if she tried to escape. (3) He then waited for the 2nd car to arrive so that the ICE officers could help with what was coming. (4) When Good saw that the ICE agents intended force her from the car, she panicked and locked the car doors (including locking her partner out of the car). (5) She then backed that car away from Ross preparing to make a run to get away.     (6) This is the key. When Ross saw that Good was intending to avoid the block that he'd set up, he walked forward, following Good's car so that he could maintain his position in front of the car. (7) Then immediately, when Good shifted the gear to drive forward and away from him, Ross drew his pistol (now that his right hand was freed from carrying the phone that he had shifted earlier) and threw himself onto the hood of the car (with a perfect prone shooting position that he'd prepared for) and began shooting. (8) He did not stop shooting until he was sure that he'd delivered a lethal shot to Good's head. (9) Afterward, he walked to Good's car, and checked to make sure that the shot was lethal. (10) After confirming that Good was either dead, or dying, Ross immediately got into his car and drove away from the crime site. (This I've heard was an illegal act.)  (11) The remaining ICE agents then blocked anyone from rushing in to give Good emergency medical help that might have kept her from dying.     Finally, in conclusion, the most import information that has been ignored (in my opinion) is that no explanation has been given about what the ICE agents were doing in the area. This is because they stopped whatever it was, and then launched a coordinated attacked on Good. And in so doing, Ross was sent ahead with the intention of blocking Good from escaping (with both his car and by standing in front of Good's car) until the rest of the ICE agents arrived. And he actually followed Good's car (when she attempted to avoid the block that he had set up by backing away from him), knowing that if she attempted to get away, she'd have to make contact with him, and thus he'd have justification for shooting her.

body: Words can have unintended consequences. When Senator Mark Kelly said, ‚ÄúYou can refuse illegal orders,‚Äù he likely did not anticipate that those words would be echoed by ICE protesters in Minneapolis. When protesters refuse to comply with ICE agents who are simply doing their jobs, escalation becomes more likely. I am not asserting that the agent‚Äôs actions were justified self-defense‚Äîthat determination belongs to others‚Äîbut the victim appears to have acted on that message by refusing orders to stop, striking the officer, however slightly, and attempting to flee. The Minnesota governor and the Minneapolis mayor should tone down their rhetoric and clearly insist on peaceful protest.  My heartfelt prayers are with the victim‚Äôs family, and the hope the unnecessary injuries and deaths can be prevented in the future.

body: From Title 1, U.S. DOJ Policy on Use of Force:  ‚ÄúFirearms may not be discharged solely to disable moving vehicles. body: If this agent was following his training, then law enforcement officers all over the nation are scratching there heads and saying WTF.  Modern law enforcement training and federal policies generally discourage or explicitly prohibit agents from stepping into the path of a moving vehicle.      Training and Tactical Positioning: Standard tactical training emphasizes maintaining a position of safety and avoiding the creation of a "self-induced" threat.      Avoidance Policy: Officers are taught not to place themselves in front of a vehicle because it creates unnecessary danger and can escalate a situation into a deadly force encounter that might otherwise be controlled.     The "Non-Kill Zone": Tactics for vehicle stops advise standing in the "non-kill zone"‚Äîa position to the rear of the driver's door‚Äîwhich prevents an officer from being struck if the driver suddenly accelerates or opens the door.     Immobilization First: Training for vehicle extractions (removing an occupant) emphasizes immobilizing the vehicle first‚Äîeither by "pinning" it with other cars or removing the keys‚Äîto ensure it cannot become a weapon.  Federal Use of Force Policy     Department of Justice (DOJ) guidelines, which govern federal agencies like ICE, include specific restrictions on firing at moving vehicles:      Duty to Move: Agents are instructed to move out of the path of a vehicle rather than using deadly force, whenever an "objectively reasonable means of defense" exists.     Restrictions on Fire: Firearms may not be discharged at a moving vehicle unless a person inside is threatening deadly force by means other than the vehicle, or the vehicle is being used as a weapon and no other defense (like stepping aside) is possible.     Prohibition on Disabling: Agents are strictly prohibited from firing at a vehicle solely to disable it or to stop a fleeing suspect who does not pose an immediate deadly threat.  In the Minneapolis incident, while the DHS claims the agent followed his training after being struck, critics and training experts have argued that placing himself in a position to be struck contradicts standard tactical procedures intended to de-escalate and ensure officer safety.

body: ü§îüòÆ Slow motion bystander video from the front shows the officer was clearly struck by the vehicle.  The female driver purposely blocked officers and refused police order to get out of the vehicle for arrest. Instead she hit the gas pedal, and hit the officer at a glancing blow, as he tried to dodge.  It all happened in just a few seconds.  The officer was obviously wounded and was limping immediately after the hit, and he was taken to a hospital and treated for injuries.  Her wife had gotten out, setup beforehand by the sidewalk, and recorded this video.  What were their intentions here?  I don‚Äôt think the suspect, in her confrontation with federal agents, woke up that day planning to get killed. I really don‚Äôt. What I do think is that she probably thought she was provoking them in a way that would end with her getting yanked out of the car, maybe shoved to the ground, detained, something ugly but non-lethal. The kind of thing that turns into a viral video where they get to play the victims and paint ICE as monsters. That‚Äôs a scenario people assume is safe, especially if they‚Äôve been around activism long enough to believe the script always ends the same way.  If her wife was already setup outside the vehicle filming the whole encounter, that tells me this wasn‚Äôt spontaneous panic. That looks like intent to capture a moment. Maybe they thought, ‚ÄúWe‚Äôll push, they‚Äôll overreact, we‚Äôll get content.‚Äù I‚Äôm sure she didn‚Äôt think she‚Äôd get shot. I‚Äôm sure she thought she was in control of the situation.  But then reality intervenes. Maybe she didn‚Äôt see the officer in front of the car. Maybe she had tunnel vision and was focused on the agent next to her. But she did accelerate forward, and once a vehicle is moving toward an officer, the situation changes instantly. At that point, whether she meant to or not, she put herself into a lethal scenario, and she lost her life.  That‚Äôs tragic. It‚Äôs also not the same thing as ‚Äúthis just happened for no reason.‚Äù  And if it turns out there‚Äôs evidence that this was coordinated...  that the wife was involved in setting this up, encouraging it, orchestrating it to get a viral confrontation...  then yeah, I think she should face charges too. Not just because someone died, but because if you help engineer a dangerous situation and someone ends up dead, you don‚Äôt get to wash your hands of it afterward.  Sympathy doesn‚Äôt mean pretending people had no agency. And accountability doesn‚Äôt mean saying someone deserved to die. Both things can be true at the same time.

body: It's better to cooperate. I am not an American, I am from Kenya, in East Africa, though US Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) look to me like they are behaving like "militia," like a "law unto themselves." But then again, aren't all of us around the world doing just that right now i.e. behaving like "militia," behaving like "laws unto ourselves?" Divine law and man-made law right now around the world, have become "cosmetic." Global society looks it's "going to the dogs" and one even gets the feeling that they could be a "World War III" in our time. Hopefully not. Even then, Alex Pretti appears to have brought about his own demise. Renee Nicole Good too, brought about her own demise. And what works in "favour" of ICE, is that ICE is not currently going around Minneapolis, USA, indiscriminately shooting dead everyone and anyone.    If a police officer anywhere in the world tells you to put your hands up, it were better you do just that. If a gangster anywhere in the world tells you to put your hands up, it were better you do just that.    In 2004, I was robbed by two guys here in Kenya. This was 22 years ago. Both guys accosted me on an early weekday morning on my way to work. One of them had a gun. I don't know whether it was a real gun or a fake gun, and I suppose I'll never know. I'm still here though, and I don't take this for granted. They asked me for my wallet and my cell phone and I gave them both. I then politely and respectfully asked them to give me back my ID and my ATM card, which were in my wallet, which they did. We then went our separate ways. It was actually more of a negotiation/transaction than it was a robbery/"mugging." I'm glad I cooperated with both those guys. What if I hadn't? Maybe I wouldn't be here right now, maybe I'd be in the "next world" right now.    It occurred to me that both guys had observed that I used the route they accosted me, on early weekday mornings on my way to work. I never used that route again in the early morning, either on weekdays or weekends. There's also a language here in Kenya known as "Sheng." Kiswahili is spoken in East and Central Africa (Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Rwanda, Burundi and the Democratic Republic of the Congo), and "Sheng" is a mixture of Kiswahili and English, is the equivalent here in Kenya of e.g. Liberian Pidgin English, Ghanaian Pidgin English or Nigerian Pidgin English. "Sheng" is not as yet fully accepted here in Kenya, even though "Sheng" began evolving here in Kenya around the 1930s. "Sheng" is still regarded a "backward language" here in Kenya.    The two guys who robbed me in 2004 spoke to me in "Sheng" and I answered them in "Sheng." The negotiation/transaction/robbery, all through, was in "Sheng." What if I had been "snobbish" and not responded to both guys in "Sheng?" I think I would have made things worse. They very likely would have felt that I was "looking down" upon them, and no one likes this.    There are things we can control, and there are things we cannot control. Two things we can control are our attitude and our temper. I almost lost my temper with Kenya police officers on patrol back in 1992. It was a Friday night and a patrol stopped my girlfriend and myself, on our way to a nightclub. They asked for our IDs which we gave them. They then said we would be booked in a police cell for "loitering" even though we had showed them our IDs and told them that we were headed to a nightclub that was a few hundred metres ahead of us, a nightclub that was even visible from where we were standing. I didn't snap though and kept my cool. I'm glad I didn't lose my cool.    My girlfriend and I spent the night in a police cell, she in the women's cell, me in the men's cell. Early the following Saturday morning I saw the cops who had arrested us the previous night, and who "acted tough and talked tough" the previous night, suddenly "shrink" and "become humble" when a certain police officer entered the police station. I knew the cop who had just entered the police station was a senior cop. I approached the senior cop and humbly and politely gave him our story. He listened and then told me to wait.    After about five minutes, my girlfriend and myself were sent for from the cells we were in. We were taken to an office where there was another senior cop. The cop I approached was actually the deputy in-charge of the police station we spent the night, and the office we were taken to was the office of the cop in-charge of the police station we spent the night. I was also respectful to the cop in-charge, and we were released immediately. The cop in-charge however told us to use a taxi the next time we used the route we were arrested. Let me put it this way, some things about a country you can only really understand if you live in that country, and some things about Africa, you can only really understand if you live in AfricaüôÇ Let me also put it this way, I understood what the cop in-charge meant when he told us to "use a taxi next time"üôÇ Like I say, some things about a country you can only really understand if you live in that countryüôÇ    Regardless of what part of the world we are from, cooperation is the best approach. We are all on edge right now all over the world, but "losing our tempers" or being defiant just for the sake of being defiant, will just be another liability, a fatal one even. It's not worth losing your life trying to be "James Bond 007," trying to be "Hardcastle and McCormick," trying to be "Harry Callahan." If a police officer anywhere in the world tells you to put your hands up, it were better you do just that. If a gangster anywhere in the world tells you to put your hands up, it were better you do just that.    Regards, Michael M. Kamau, Nairobi, Kenya, East Africa, 25th January 2026.

body: From Adam Miller   ¬∑ "It is clear that US citizens' ignorance of federal laws and law enforcement duties, procedures, and limits of authority is getting to the point where it is deadly. I spent probably 3 hours watching and re-watching, and finding every single video and angle I could of the situation in Minnesota yesterday and came to one immovable conclusion based off of what I saw and what I know from a professional standpoint. This is long, but please give it a read. "As a former officer, let me make something clear: ICE agents ARE NOT police officers, deputy sheriffs, or troopers. They are not local/state law enforcement. They are not federal criminal law enforcement. They have an INCREDIBLY limited scope of authority, and that scope of authority exists in detaining and arresting with probable cause and/or SIGNED WARRANTS those investigated and suspected of being in the US illegally. "They cannot just pull anyone over for a traffic violation or because their car is in a place they don't want it. They have NO authority to pull people over for ANYTHING other than immigration enforcement- and even then that involves probable cause, such as a known vehicle of someone they have been tracking, or a warrant. On very rare occasions they have the legal authority to pull someone over if they are threatening the lives of others, but that was not happening in this case. They do not have the training nor the authority to pull ANYONE else over. They cannot arrest legal citizens. They cannot detain legal citizens without probable cause to believe they might not be legal. They have ZERO authority to be attempting to force entry into a vehicle- without even identifying themselves, without a warrant, without exigent circumstances such as a life being directly threatened- that is trying to drive down the street without probable cause in relation to IMMIGRATION ENFORCEMENT. "This ENTIRE situation in Minnesota was outside of the scope of legal authority from the get go. None of it was done within the scope of authority of ICE. Every single behavior those agents made was procedurally incorrect, done without proper authority, and was based off of intimidation and the assumption that people do not understand the law and their rights in regards to interactions with ICE. "On no planet should an officer, agent, or any human being ever step in front of a car in 'drive' that is actively trying to leave and use their body as a shield to prevent a person from LEGALLY LEAVING a situation in which they are not legally being detained. It takes maybe a week of any kind of actual law enforcement training to understand that under NO CIRCUMSTANCES do you ever place yourself in front of a vehicle in 'drive.' That agent had every single opportunity to simply take two steps to the right and not be standing directly in front of a vehicle attempting to conduct their legal right to drive away. "You can see the wheels are turned, [Renee] backed up and turned them to the right, moved forward a bit to leave, couldn't because an agent was standing in front of her, and continued to try to leave by TURNING HER WHEELS TO THE RIGHT and moving forward. He continually chose to stand there and not allow her to legally leave as she had every single right to do. The officer pulling on her door and banging on her window and swearing at her had ZERO authority to order her out of her vehicle or attempt to make entry into her vehicle. NONE. A single day of actual training of the legal scope of authority and the LAW would've prevented that from happening. "You now have a frightened citizen being blockaded by immigration agents (with another person in her vehicle) who had zero obligation to follow legally invalid orders from that agent, being blocked in and having a fully grown, masked man attempting to make entry into her car. If this were reversed, every single person would immediately feel she had every reasonable expectation to fear for her safety. It doesn't matter if she knew it was ICE because the agents weren't even acting in their scope of authority anyway. "Whether or not she made the right decision by very CLEARLY- based off of how hard her wheels were turned and how low and to the driver corner windshield that shot was fired- trying to drive to the left of that agent is IRRELEVANT in the picture as a whole. None of this would have happened if those agents had done even one single thing correctly. Not just correctly, but within their legal scope of authority. Every single moment of that interaction was escalated by untrained, unprofessional, procedurally inept "agents" who not only had zero control of themselves but everything around them. And not because they are helpless, but because their actions that did not fall under their scope of power CAUSED this. Their tempers, lack of training, and the knowledge that they can get away with violating their own scope of authority caused this. "I will always be the first to defend law enforcement when lethal force very clearly is required. But this was not even remotely the case, and as an actual TRAINED professional in that field with experience and understanding of both the law and procedures, there is no justification for this- and it would benefit EVERYONE to actually read up on the laws, scope of authority, and use a single shred of common sense to see that this situation was started, escalated, and caused by the ICE agents involved. I have zero respect for those in power who are ignorant of the scope of their authority and abuse it at the cost of lives around them."

body: This was a chaotic, poorly controlled ICE operation, and that‚Äôs the core of the problem. These agents are not regular patrol police and do not have the same level of training or experience in traffic stops, crowd control, or dynamic vehicle encounters. On top of that, ICE has gone through mass hiring pushes, and even people inside law enforcement will tell you that many newer agents are being pushed into the field without the depth of training and experience that situations like this absolutely require. That difference matters, because this situation escalated in seconds in exactly the way better training and better tactics are meant to prevent.  Yes, a car can be a deadly weapon. But use-of-force policy across North America is very clear on one point: you do not step into the path of a vehicle and then use that as justification to shoot unless there is truly no other option and an immediate, unavoidable threat to life. From the video, one thing is already obvious: the officer was not run over, not struck, and not injured in any way that would require hospitalization. You can debate what she should or shouldn‚Äôt have done, but you cannot claim this was a case of an officer being hit or nearly killed. The footage simply does not support that.  This is where training and judgment matter. Properly trained police are taught to create distance, move out of a vehicle‚Äôs path, use containment, and de-escalate whenever possible. Shooting into a car is supposed to be a last resort, not a first reflex. The fact that this escalated to lethal force so quickly is exactly why people are questioning the competence of the operation and the decisions that were made.  And there‚Äôs a bigger picture people keep ignoring. In 2024, more people were deported than in 2025, yet under the Trump administration we‚Äôre suddenly seeing more chaos, more botched operations, and now an American citizen is dead. A mother. That isn‚Äôt ‚Äúlaw and order.‚Äù That‚Äôs what happens when enforcement turns into political theater instead of professional, controlled policing.  No one is arguing that people should ignore lawful orders. But the state also has a responsibility to use force proportionally, competently, and only as a last resort. That is why there is an investigation, and that is why any serious leader would wait for the findings instead of rushing out a political verdict. If this were as clear-cut as some people want to pretend, there wouldn‚Äôt already be this many red flags visible in the video.

body: Did you see the CONFUSED look on the officer's face when he was examining the Man's ID (which he handed over).  This happened to me too.  I was filming ICE officers at Home Depot in Los Angeles in 2025, quietly, standing far away, minding my own business. An officer approached me and asked for my ID.  As I was media, I didn't want to get in an argument, so I just handed him my Passport Card.  For those that don't know, a "Passport Card" is the same size as a Driver's License, and you can request it when you apply for a Passport.  Essentially it IS a Passport. Only citizens can obtain one.... And the ICE Agent looked at it with the same CONFUSED expression.  He said, "What is this?  I said, "It's a Passport Card."  Then he showed it to another ICE officer, who gave him the Thumb's Up .... So Let's Get This Straight: "The ICE Officer who is in charge of identifying a person's citizenship, DID NOT KNOW what a Passport Card is . . . just in case you are wondering how "trained" these ICE officers are.

body: I saw the full videos from every angle.  It comes down to this.. the lady was clearly not aggressive in her demeanor when she was being talked to (was actually smiling), but then either got frightened or just resistant when the one ICE officer tried to open her door.   The ICE agent who shot her was in her blind spot coming across from the other side in front and she didnt see him.  When she put in drive, she clearly turned sharply but not enough to avoid the ICE agent from the corner and he shot her.   The victim's sister (or other relative) told her to 'drive baby drive!' so maybe that influenced her also. It is one of those unfortunate gray areas that you can make a case on either side that it was excessive or justified force.  There will never be a technical 'correct' answer to this.  Will all be interpretation.  I would have personally preferred they just take her plate down and arrest her later for obstruction.  In the end, an American mother with no criminal record was killed and that is tragic.

body: Its still hard to tell.   What I don't get though is, like I can totally get the "he was fearing for his life" argument if it was just the one shot...   But 2 and 3 were overkill and the 'effing b' comment, knowing he just popped her in the head 3 times, is not a trauma response as one would expect if you just panic-fired your weapon in the face of danger.   Also the fact he just happened to switch hands with his phone to free up his shootin hand, when if he never did that his response would been more likely to dive out of the way because having to swap hands then shoot while thinking you're being run over would take longer than just moving out of the way.  Also she backed up, if she wanted to hit him on purpose she woulda done what any one trying to run someone over woulda done, floor it. Backing up implies she had intent to clear obstacles.   Also why did she suddenly decide to move? So instantaneously that she left her partner behind? What did she see? What did she notice? I have so many questions...  Theres too many variables that dont make sense. The Math isnt fully mathing. I hope more footage comes out, maybe even other bodycams or dashcams from the other agents, that would be a good pov I think, might answer more questions.

One would imagine the front of a vehicle you have no control over is the last place you want to be, especially if you had been dragged by another vehicle before.  Also, pretty sure most trained agents/officers or even a child could tell you a human body will not be able to do anything against a moving vehicle, even less so if the driver is incapacitated (e.g. shot or injured) with his/her foot on the gas. Taking out his gun first, instead of reacting to get out of the way, is really baffling. If he was much more situationally aware or better trained, he wouldn't be in that position in front of the vehicle to be "endangered" and no need for the "self-defence" shots.   No matter what Renee Good's intentions were prior to this incident (protesting/harassing ICE/just going about her day), is does not justify having her life taken away. This whole incident was simply a tragedy. Probably so much more could have been done in hindsight, and it's unfortunate that things had to turn out this way.

body: The video is paused at a bad spot for the narrator to talk, but her wheels were straight forward when she began to accelorate, but turned to the right a split second later when the guy in front drew his gun. I think she was trying to get away from the guy at her window, but when she backed up, turning the other way, it positioned her car with the man (who had filmed her wife) in front of her vehicle. In trying to get away from the man at her door, I'm not sure she realized that she had squared up with someone i  front of her. The whole thing is tragic & shouldn't have happened. Look at a video that isn't repeatedly paused & watch her wheel straighten & then turn. I'm not sure if ICE agents are trained the same way as other LE, but my Navy Police training was clear that if someone tries to hit you, that's deadly force & an officer may shoot center mass to stop the threat. From another article I read, the man in front DID aim center mass. You don't shoot to kill, you shoot to stop a threat to your life. The guy at her door shot her in the head. That is not center mass & he was close enough to aim center mass.

body: To suggest that ‚Äúshe shouldn‚Äôt have driven away‚Äù or that ‚Äúthe agent was merely doing his duty‚Äù misses the profound moral reality of the situation. No human life is ever expendable because of confusion, fear, or a momentary lapse in judgment. The use of lethal force represents the ultimate threshold of responsibility; it is never a default response to a stressful encounter. That state officials were later denied access to critical evidence, and that the Justice Department refrained from pursuing a civil rights investigation‚Äîdespite the resignations of federal prosecutors deeply troubled by that choice‚Äîshould disturb anyone who values justice, accountability, and the moral underpinnings of the rule of law. True governance demands that those entrusted with power exercise it with both wisdom and restraint.

body: S/o to atty Andrew Branca! I would defer to him. My thoughts:   1. You should only shoot if the threat of death or serious bodily harm is imminent.   2. Irving is absolutely right. If you choose to shoot (obviously to stop an imminent threat), you have to make sure that the reason you began shooting is fulfilled, ie the threat is incapacitated. *Also, this could mean not only threat to yourself, but threat to others.   3. If you're carrying a pistol, 1 shot may definitely not be enough, thus multiple shots are needed. Also, consider that in the moment, which could be just seconds, you may not know what is or is not hitting the intended target.   For those who do carry and are trained, I presume most of them know these things. For others who are untrained, or don't have extensive experience, it may be good to be open enough to at least entertain multiple points of view. IMO, Irving is correct throughout.

Firing multiple rounds at a person‚Äôs head from close range, especially when not under imminent threat, meets the legal definition of murder under Minnesota Statute ¬ß609.19, which defines murder as causing death "by intent to effect the death of another." body: Im a retired police officer,   These guys are woefully misinformed.  The guy in the white is trying really hard to play mental gymnastics here and he's flat out wrong.   Toward the end, claims, you can't assume she would drive on and pose a...threat, wrong.. wrong..wrong...  She just refused to obey lawful commands. And she used her vehicle in a reckless manner and is now attempting to flee, which puts it into  felony flight.   we know from history, this often results in pursuits that puts the broader public in danger that has led to innocent bystanders being hit and killed, so for him to claim we can't assume that she would continue to drive on, which would result in a risk to others is absolutely wrong.   That is the only assumption that can be made in a situation like this. Based on historical premise and common sense.  This is why felony flight, where lethal force is authorized and exists in the first place.  It exists to neutralize a threat that has demonstrated a gross disregard for the lives and safety of others  and puts the general public at risk.  As far as them talking about the additional shots,  No, that third shot is not relevant. Sitting here and microanalyzing, how many shots or whether or not the shots to the side matter is ridiculous, and it's not a legal standard.   The standard is whether or not lethal force was applicable or not.  Deadly force is not authorized for mere flight, but it is authorized when a suspect‚Äôs actions create an imminent threat of death or serious bodily injury to officers or others.   Her stepping on the gas with officers surrounding her vehicle now puts a use of force continuum into lethal force, and she is demonstrating a clear threat to those around her and operating her vehicle in a reckless manner with disregard to life, which now places it in felony flight, which makes lethal force authorized.  That distinction is well established in federal policy and Supreme Court precedent.  1. Intent is not the legal standard. Under Graham v. Connor, force is judged by objective reasonableness, not the suspect‚Äôs subjective intent. Officers are not required or expected to determine what someone ‚Äúmeant‚Äù to do in a split-second encounter. The analysis focuses on observable conduct and the danger it creates, not later explanations or claimed intent.  2. A vehicle becomes a deadly weapon when used recklessly. When a driver accelerates, maneuvers, or otherwise operates a vehicle in close proximity to officers or the public after refusing lawful commands, the vehicle is treated as a deadly weapon. This alone can justify deadly force because it creates an immediate risk of serious injury or death.  3. Wheel angle and split-second positioning are legally irrelevant. Courts have repeatedly rejected frame-by-frame hindsight analysis. Officers are not required to assess steering angle, tire direction, or speculate about last-moment evasive maneuvers. What matters is whether a reasonable officer at that moment perceived an imminent threat based on the totality of the circumstances.  4. Officers are not required to wait to be struck or injured. The law does not require officers to absorb harm before acting. Once conduct creates an immediate and substantial risk, deadly force may be used to stop that threat.  5. Felony flight changes the analysis. Under Tennessee v. Garner, deadly force may be used to prevent escape when officers have probable cause to believe the suspect poses a significant threat of death or serious physical injury to officers or others. Flight that itself creates danger‚Äîsuch as reckless vehicle use‚Äîmeets this standard. Relevant Supreme Court cases: Graham v. Connor ‚Äì establishes the objective reasonableness standard; intent is irrelevant. Tennessee v. Garner ‚Äì allows deadly force to prevent escape when the suspect poses a significant threat. Scott v. Harris and Plumhoff v. Rickard ‚Äì confirm that dangerous vehicle flight can justify deadly force and reject hindsight second-guessing.  Bottom line: The law prioritizes stopping imminent danger, not guessing intent or dissecting wheel angles after the fact. When a suspect uses a vehicle in a reckless manner that places officers or the public at immediate risk, deadly force is legally justified under Supreme Court precedent, regardless of claimed intent or microscopic analysis of vehicle movement.

body: Gaslighting works   when it regulates fear   faster   than truth can land.    brain asks only one question:    ‚ÄúWhat story lets me feel safe right now?‚Äù    Not: ‚ÄúWhat is true?‚Äù    Under threat,   most humans side with whoever looks strongest.    Because strength feels like protection.    So     even if the act is horrifying, people unconsciously think:   ‚ÄúI‚Äôd rather be aligned with power   than exposed to chaos.‚Äù    That alignment dulls moral clarity.    Language anesthetizes violence  Words like:    ‚Äúself-defense‚Äù  ‚Äúprotocol‚Äù  ‚Äúincident‚Äù  ‚Äúofficer-involved‚Äù  do not describe reality.    They numb it.    The brain hears abstraction   instead of blood.    Abstraction reduces empathy.     Reduced empathy allows denial.    Eventually people say: ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know what really happened.‚Äù    Admitting the truth   would require people to face:    complicity  powerlessness  horror  That is unbearable for many.    So they choose the story that lets them stay psychologically intact.    This is not courage.   This is self-preservation through denial.    The more emotional the truth is delivered,   the more people cling to the lie   that calms them.    That is the trap.    Repetition does not persuade.   It normalizes.    Once a phrase is heard enough times,   the brain treats it as familiar.    Familiar feels safe.   Safe feels true.    Gaslighting works   not because the lie is good,  but because the truth is too destabilizing   for most people to hold.    you would rather be horrified   than anesthetized  That puts you in the minority.    This is not new.   This is how every violent system survives.

body: Excellent analysis.  I used to do photo analysis as part of my work.  A couple things I would add to the chronology that no one else has mentioned.  I slowed down the 1st vid on the day of the shooting to 25%.  Some points on my chronology come from my viewing of later videos.  Ross is on the scene first.  He circles Ms. Good's car, which is running during the entire incident, & films her saying, 'That's fine, Dude, I'm not mad at you.'  The officer continues to walk around her vehicle followed by Ms. Good's partner.  Ms. Good has started to move her vehicle (Ross is at her rear passenger corner at this point), but stops because a gray pickup is approaching on her L side.  The gray pickup was unmarked.  It stops.  Ms. Good waves with her arm a few times for the vehicle to go ahead of her.  Instead, you can see two ICE agents get out of the vehicle.  It is the agent in gray who was in the passenger seat who says, 'Get out of the car!  Get out of the f-ing car!'  You can see the puff of vapor as he says, that 1st 'car'.  Contradictorily, as he has been telling her to 'Get out of the car!', he is pointing with his extended L arm to the far side of the road as though he wants her to pull over there.  This reflects contradictory instructions.  Others have heard an officer telling her to move her vehicle & Ms. Good say that she would move it.  Both agents who came from the gray pickup are hostile & aggressive.  After Ross has filmed a complete circle around Ms. Good's vehicle, he stops by his own vehicle.  The filmer of the 1st video pans the camera briefly to the L but when it returns to  back again, you can see that the position of Ross' driver's side door has changed.  Ross continues to move around to the front of Ms. Good's vehicle.  You can see his blurry moving reflection around the front of her car in the damp pavement visible under her car.  Three things happen nearly simultaneously.  The agent in black (the driver of the gray pickup) is pulling on Ms. Good's handle & reaching into her car.  Ms. Good's partner is trying to get in the R passenger side, which is apparently locked.  Agent Ross has stopped near the driver's side corner of her vehicle & is reaching for his weapon.  Ms. Good is dealing with stress & 4 people around her car, 3 of which are hostile.  She probably understandably panicked & wanted to leave.  Ross does not issue any warning.  You can see that the car is not moving forward as he pulls his gun.  Ross takes 3 shots as the vehicle passes him.  His feet are well to the L of the driver's side tire when he takes the 1st shot-- see the position of his feet as the vapor from the 1st shot is visible.  The 2nd & 3rd shots were through the open driver's side window at point blank range.  The shot to the L side of her head-- obviously the 2nd or 3rd shot when Ross was at the side of the car-- was almost certainly the shot that caused her death.  None of the shots were necessary as Ross had PLACED HIMSELF near the front of her car.  He stepped aside easily.  He appears to LEAN IN & purposely took the 1st, 2nd, & 3rd shots when he was completely away from the car.  Ross had filmed her license plate, so if there were going to be charges, they could have looked up her address through the Motor Vehicle Administration easily.  None of the legal opinions I've watched suggest that she broke any law.  Not only does he fatally shoot Ms. Good, but he puts others in danger in the line of fire: her partner on the R side of the car, three people standing on the sidewalk beyond the car (one appears to duck as seen in another video), & potentially other persons on the street & in houses.  Because Ross shoots a driver of a moving vehicle, the vehicle goes wildly out of control for about 1/4 of a mile, putting people in danger who may have been in the path of that vehicle as well as people in the white car that was demolished from the force of the collision down the street.  The fact that Mr. Ross purposely paused at the corner of Ms. Good's vehicle & at some point had switched the cell phone he had been using for filming from his R to his L hand, & putting his hand on or over his gun, shows that he was preparing to shoot Ms. Good.  All before she was moving forward.  Isn't this 'Intent before the fact/premeditation'?  After the shooting as Ms. Good's vehicle is traveling down the street out of control, Mr. Ross says, 'F-ing bitch'.  This not only shows a complete lack of concern or remorse, it shows a high level of hostility & callousness.  Mr. Ross, nor any of the other officers in the vicinity run to the crashed vehicle to offer aid.  Eventually Mr. Ross does walk down to the vehicle, but he only glances into the vehicle for less than a second.  He does not attempt CPR.  On his way back up to the scene of the shooting, he yells to other agents to, 'Call 911.'  Why didn't Ross use his OWN cell phone to call 911 after he shot Ms. Good instead of standing there cursing the woman he had just shot?  He walks up & down the street just fine, obviously uninjured.  The refusal of agents to let a physician in to attend to the injured Ms. Good is another serious but separate issue.  Apparently no one attended Ms. Good until the paramedics arrived, which was reportedly 20 minutes after the shooting.  Witnesses said that the paramedics had to walk a distance from the emergency vehicle to Ms. Good because ICE vehicles were blocking the road.  Why didn't they move their vehicles to give access to the ambulance?  The paramedics had to bodily carry Ms. Good from her car some distance away to the emergency vehicle.  The agents' actions show IMO: lack of coordination, conflicting instructions, malice, premeditation, purposely putting oneself near jeopardy, creating a dangerous situation, unnecessarily using lethal force, endangering several others in the line of fire, causing a vehicle to go dangerously out of control, failing to render aid, refusing medical aid for the victim, & blocking access for emergency vehicles.  Agent Ross in particular showed a callous disregard for life & used excessive force.  Leaning in to shoot a woman 3x in the face & calling her a 'f-ing bitch' immediately afterwards, reflects a person who is extremely hostile who should not be carrying a gun, let alone be an 'officer'.  There is clearly wrongdoing here by several agents.  The shooting should be thoroughly investigated.  Agent Ross should be prosecuted, jailed, &/or-- ironically-- deported!

body: Multiple federal ICE agents repeatedly instructed the driver to stop and exit her vehicle. At the time, agents were positioned at the driver‚Äôs window and around the vehicle. Despite these lawful commands, the driver continued operating the car while her spouse urged her to proceed. Encouraging another individual to operate a motor vehicle in a manner that places law enforcement officers and the public at risk may constitute aiding or abetting a criminal act. A vehicle used in this way can legally be classified as a deadly weapon. By choosing to drive while agents were in close proximity, the driver knowingly created a dangerous and potentially lethal situation for herself, the officers involved, and nearby civilians. This tragic outcome resulted from a series of deliberate decisions made during a highly charged encounter. While the loss of life is undeniably heartbreaking‚Äîparticularly given that she was a wife and mother‚Äîthe escalation stemmed from a refusal to comply with lawful instructions and a conscious decision to proceed in a manner that endangered others. Law enforcement officers are required to perform their duties under intense and often dangerous conditions.
